<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E6FF30FF25FD20FC35BCC9" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E6FF30FF25FD20FC6DBDC5" blockId="177.[151,1437,577,1358]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FF25FD20FEA7BDE9" bold="true" box="[199,345,685,710]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Description.</emphasis>
Face finely rugose; black with red brown spots (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FC70FD20FC03BDE9" box="[914,1021,685,710]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61G</figureCitation>
). Apter, meso- and metanotum with weak lateral expansions but without clear traces of wings (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FCC5FD5CFC78BDC5" box="[807,902,721,746]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61J</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E6FF30FF25FD78FE87BC55" blockId="177.[151,1437,577,1358]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">
Male. Ninth abdominal tergite globular, at apical margin with a pair of narrow styliform projections (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FACAFD78FA71BC21" box="[1320,1423,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61K</figureCitation>
). Tenth abdominal tergite narrow band shaped, little widened towards and grooved in midline. Subgenital plate with apical margin projecting between bases of styli; projecting part laterally concave, at tip narrow truncate, not fully reaching tip of styli.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E6FF30FF25FC08FC35BCC9" blockId="177.[151,1437,577,1358]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">
Female. Seventh abdominal sternite with a pair of small pits in posterior area; following intersegmental membrane with a groove. Subgenital plate with a triangular central and smaller and shorter lobular lateral lobes (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FF7DFC40FF04BCC9" box="[159,250,973,998]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Figs. 61</figureCitation>
H–I). Ovipositor slightly curved; tip simple, subacute (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FC83FC40FC41BCC9" box="[865,959,973,998]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="174.[151,250,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@174.[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetPageId="174" captionText="FIGURE 60. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–E, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (C–D) and female (E); F–G, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; H, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; I–J, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female type BrW17.124.—Lateral view (A, C, E–F, H–I), dorsal view (B, D, G, J). Scale 10 mm (Brunner's types not to scale)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">
Fig. 
<date id="AF4E038097E6FF30FC77FC40FC41BCC9" box="[917,959,973,998]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" value="1960-01">60I</date>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E6FF30FF25FC7CFCA5BA62" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E6FF30FF25FC7CFCA5BA62" blockId="177.[151,1437,577,1358]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FF25FC7CFEB2BB25" bold="true" box="[199,332,1009,1034]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species had been synonymised by 
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E6FF30FCF9FC7FFC40BB25" author="Karny, H. H." box="[795,958,1009,1034]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" pagination="501 - 534" refId="ref187723" refString="Karny, H. H. (1928 f) Revision der Gryllacriden der Stuttgarter Naturaliensammlung. Zoologische Jahrbucher, Abteilung fur Systematik, Oekologie und Geographie der Tiere, 55, 501 - 534." type="journal article" year="1928">Karny (1928f)</bibRefCitation>
under 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E6FF30FBEDFC7FFF25BB01" authority="(Walker, 1869)" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1869" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Neanias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis" subGenus="Eremus">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FBEDFC7FFACDBB26" box="[1039,1331,1009,1033]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Neanias (Eremus) basalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E6FF30FAA6FC7CFF2DBB01" author="Walker, F." pageId="177" pageNumber="178" refId="ref189674" refString="Walker, F. (1869) Catalogue of the Specimens of Dermaptera Saltatoria and Supplement to the Blattariae in the Collection of the British Museum. Pt 1. [iv +] 1 - 224; London (British Museum of Natural History)." type="book" year="1869">Walker, 1869</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. He probably had not seen the 
<typeStatus id="044B9BE297E6FF30FDD3FB98FD60BB01" box="[561,670,1045,1070]" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">holotypes</typeStatus>
of both species in direct comparison, both are females. Although the shapes of the subgenital plates of both females are similar with a large, roughly triangular central lobe and a pair of smaller lateral lobes, the central plate of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E6FF30FDBDFBD3FCFEBB5A" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[607,768,1117,1141]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geniculatus">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FDBDFBD3FCFEBB5A" box="[607,768,1117,1141]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">E. geniculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is triangular with a nearly subacute tip (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FB27FBD0FAD3BB59" box="[1221,1325,1117,1142]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61H</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E6FF30FF75FB0FFEF8BBB6" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[151,262,1153,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Neanias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FF75FB0FFEF8BBB6" box="[151,262,1153,1177]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">E. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is more lobular with the tip obtuse (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FD5DFB0CFCDABBB5" box="[703,804,1153,1178]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61F</figureCitation>
). More specific differences can be found in the seventh abdominal sternite, which has in 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E6FF30FDF8FB2BFD75BB92" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[538,651,1189,1213]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Neanias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FDF8FB2BFD75BB92" box="[538,651,1189,1213]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">E. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a short appendage in middle with strongly stiffened margins and a groove in middle and laterally of that appendage, the apical margin of the sternite is also grooved (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FB0FFB44FAAFBBCD" box="[1261,1361,1225,1250]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61F</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E6FF30FA66FB47FEE6BA2A" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geniculatus">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FA66FB47FEE6BA2A" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">E. geniculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the seventh sternite has a pair of small pits in apical area and the apical margin is simply convex, but there is a groove in the intersegmental membrane between the sternite and the subgenital plate (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E6FF30FAE9FA9CFA9EBA05" box="[1291,1376,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="177" pageNumber="178">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
H–I). Moreover, the ovipositor is distinctly shorter than in 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E6FF30FD07FABBFCADBA62" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[741,851,1333,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Neanias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="177" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E6FF30FD07FABBFCADBA62" box="[741,851,1333,1357]" italics="true" pageId="177" pageNumber="178">E. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
